+#
+# List of tests that should not be run by test/Makefile, for various reasons:
+#   1. Does not run with jtreg -samevm mode
+#   2. Causes problems in jtreg -samevm mode for jtreg or tests that follow it
+#   3. The test is too slow or consumes too many system resources
+#   4. The test fails when run on any official build systems
+#
+# It is possible that a test being on this list is a mistake, and that some
+#   other test in samevm mode caused tests to fail, mistakes happen.
+#
+# Tests marked @ignore are not run by test/Makefile, but harmless to be listed.
+#
+# Tests that explicitly state "@run main/othervm ...", and are not listed here,
+#   will be run in the same batch as the samevm tests.
+#
+# Shell tests are othervm by default.
+#
+# List items are testnames followed by labels, all MUST BE commented
+#   as to why they are here and use a label:
+#     generic-all   Problems on all platforms
+#     generic-ARCH  Where ARCH is one of: x64, i586, ppc64, ppc64le, s390x, aarch64 etc.
+#     OSNAME-all    Where OSNAME is one of: linux, windows, macosx, aix
+#     OSNAME-ARCH   Specific on to one OSNAME and ARCH, e.g. macosx-x64
+#     OSNAME-REV    Specific on to one OSNAME and REV, e.g. macosx-10.7.4
+#
+# More than one label is allowed but must be on the same line comma seperated,
+# without spaces.
+# If there are several lines mentioning the same test, the last one is used.
+#
+#############################################################################
+#
+# Running the tests:
+#    cd test && make JT_HOME=jtreg_home PRODUCT_HOME=jdk_home jdk_all
+#  Or instead of jdk_all, use any of the jdk_* targets.
+#
+# Samevm Notes:
+#  * Although some tests may have only been seen to fail on some platforms,
+#    they might be flagged as 'generic-all' because the problem they have
+#    could cause hidden slowdowns on other platforms.
+#    Most samevm problems will be generic-all, but windows usually dislikes
+#    them the most.
+#    Address already in use or connection errors indicate a generic port issue.
+#    (this is not necessarily a samevm issue, but an issue for running the tests
+#     on shared machines, two people or two test runs will collide).
+#  * Samevm problem (windows in particular) is not closing all input/output
+#  * Samevm problem when a test calls setSecurityManager()
+#  * Samevm problem with setHttps*() is used? (not exactly sure here)
+#  * Samevm problem when stuffing system properties with non Strings or anything
+#  * Samevm problem when changing vm settings, or registering any vm actions
+#  * Samevm problems with deleteOnExit(), if it must happen at end of test
+#  * Samevm problems with URLClassLoader? (no details here)
+#  * Samevm problems with dependence on predictable GC or finalizations
+#
+# Any of the above problems may mean the test needs to be flagged as "othervm".
+#
+#############################################################################
+#
+# Fixing the tests:
+#
+# Some tests just may need to be run with "othervm", and that can easily be
+#   done by adding a @run line (or modifying any existing @run):
+#      @run main/othervm NameOfMainClass
+#   Make sure this @run follows any use of @library.
+#   Otherwise, if the test is a samevm possibility, make sure the test is
+#     cleaning up after itself, closing all streams, deleting temp files, etc.
+#
+# Keep in mind that the bug could be in many places, and even different per
+#   platform, it could be a bug in any one of:
+#      - the testcase
+#      - the jdk (jdk classes, native code, or hotspot)
+#      - the native compiler
+#      - the javac compiler
+#      - the OS (depends on what the testcase does)
+#
+# If you managed to really fix one of these tests, here is how you can
+#    remove tests from this list:
+#  1. Make sure test passes on all platforms with samevm, or mark it othervm
+#  2. Make sure test passes on all platforms when run with it's entire group
+#  3. Make sure both VMs are tested, -server and -client, if possible
+#  4. Use your favorite build and test system to verify these results
+#  5. Delete lines in this file, include the changes with your test changes
+#
+# You may need to repeat your testing 2 or even 3 times to verify good
+#   results, some of these samevm failures are not very predictable.
+#

+#!/bin/bash
+
+# run_jtreg.sh is a little helper script to run jtreg tests with SAPJVM 8 +
+# see http://openjdk.java.net/jtreg/index.html for details about what jtreg is
+
+help_output()
+{
+  echo "run_jtreg.sh <vm-version> <tests> [-jdkdir <jdk-image-directory>] [-testdir <directory>] [<optional other jtreg options>]"
+  echo "... runs automatic (non-manual) jdk jtreg tests."
+  echo "Some tests work only with a full jdk-image, so setting the jdk-image dir is recommended (specified via -jdkdir <jdk-image-directory>)."
+  echo "To specify another jtreg test root directory, please set -testdir <directory>."
+  echo " "
+  echo "Currently VM versions 8 and 11 are supported."
+  echo "More jtreg details cen be found at : http://openjdk.java.net/jtreg/"
+  echo " "
+  echo "Example:"
+  echo "--------------"
+  echo "execution of java/net tests on the local SAPJVM8"
+  echo "  run_jtreg.sh 8 java/net"
+  echo " "
+  echo "execution of some default jdk tests on the local SAPJVM8 image"
+  echo "  run_jtreg.sh 8 default -jdkdir sapjvm_8"
+  echo " "
+  echo "execution of the default hotspot tests on the local SAPJVM8 image"
+  echo "  run_jtreg.sh 8 hsdefault -jdkdir sapjvm_8"
+  echo " "
+  echo "execution of java/nio tests on a specified JDK image"
+  echo "  run_jtreg.sh 8 java/nio  -jdkdir /opt/mydir/myjdk8"
+  echo " "
+  echo "execution of hotspot compiler tests on a specified JDK image, using the jtreg dir of hotspot"
+  echo "  run_jtreg.sh 8 compiler  -jdkdir sapjvm_8 -testdir /my_sapjvm/bas2/sapjvm/dev/6/hotspot/test"
+  echo " "
+  echo "execution of all the langtools tests on a specified JDK image, using the test-directory of langtools"
+  echo "  run_jtreg.sh 8 test -jdkdir sapjvm_8 -testdir /mydir/j2se/18/langtools"
+  echo " "
+  echo "For details on jtreg options, please see the jtreg help or http://openjdk.java.net/jtreg/command-help.html"
+  echo "execution of java/net tests on a specified JDK with a jtreg option to be passed to the VM set:"
+  echo "  run_jtreg.sh 8 java/net -jdkdir /opt/mydir/myjdk8 -vmoption:-XtraceSpawn*"
+}
+
+
+# and omit -agentvm
+if test $# -lt 1 ; then
+  echo Give Java version to test as first argument, followed by tests to be executed
+  help_output
+  exit
+fi
+VM_VERSION=$1
+
+# JTREG_VERSION is a number
+JTREG_VERSION=$1
+
+# JTREG=/usr/work/openjdk/tools/jtreg_sapjvm_dev/bin/jtreg
+# JTREG=/usr/work/d003504/Distributed/utils/apps/jtreg_sapjvm_dev/bin/jtreg
+JTREG=/usr/work/openjdk/tools/jtreg_sapjvm_o_jdk/bin/jtreg
+unset JAVA_HOME
+
+# a little bit of help output ...
+if test x"$VM_VERSION" = "x-h" -o x"$VM_VERSION" = "x-help"
+then
+  help_output
+  exit
+fi
+
+# graphical help from jtreg (needs DISPLAY set!!)
+if test x"$VM_VERSION" = "x-onlinehelp" -o x"$VM_VERSION" = "x-onlineHelp"
+then
+  $JTREG -onlineHelp
+  exit
+fi
+
+# increase timeout factor to get less sporadic failing tests; use concurrent tests on agent vm
+# ignore quietly tests marked with @ignore they usually fail and create trouble
+# -a : only non-manual = automatic tests
+# -conc:auto is dangerous on some virtualized AIX servers -> can kill the server completely
+# so use -conc:4 instead this should be still pretty good on almost all of our machines
+# -ea / -esa : enable assertions / enable system assertions
+
+# PJ 2019-08-21 change verbose option to get less output
+#JTREGFLAGS="-timeoutFactor:5 -agentvm -conc:4 -ignore:quiet -k:!ignore -verbose:summary -a -ea -esa"
+JTREGFLAGS="-timeoutFactor:1 -agentvm -conc:4 -ignore:quiet -k:!ignore -verbose:nopass -a -ea -esa"
+
+# handling Cygwin
+uname_a=`uname -a`
+
+# that does not work on HP-UX: if [[ $uname_a =~ Cygwin* ]] ; then
+if test `echo $uname_a | grep -c 'Cygwin'` != 0
+then
+  echo "run_jtreg.sh is running on Cygwin / Windows"
+  CYG_P4ROOT=`cygpath $P4ROOT`
+  JTREG_LOCAL=$CYG_P4ROOT/bas2/sapjvm_tools/dev/jtreg/4.1
+  JTREG=$JTREG_LOCAL/bin/jtreg
+  # Cygwin by default eliminates most environment variables; we must explicitly say what we want to add
+  # SHELLOPTS is needed because it contains igncr which is needed for a lot of *.sh scripts
+  CYG_ADDENV="-e:SHELLOPTS"
+  ISCYGWIN=1
+fi
+
+# choose a text about the default java used (output it later once we know about -jdkdir)
+default_java_text=""
+
+# some sanity checks for local java (build directory and as fallback image directory)
+if test -r $VM_VERSION/bin/java; then
+  default_java_text="$VM_VERSION/bin/java found, which could be used for jtreg test execution. However for a few tests we recommend to set -jdkdir  because some tests expect the exact jdk-image layout."
+else
+  # consider the jdk image
+  if test -r sapjvm_$VM_VERSION/bin/java; then
+    default_java_text="$VM_VERSION/bin/java not found, using sapjvm_$VM_VERSION/bin/java for test execution instead." 
+    VM_VERSION=sapjvm_$VM_VERSION
+  fi
+fi
+
+shift
+
+# check for -jdkdir <dir> setting at the end of argument list
+FOUND_JDK_DIR=0
+# check for -testdir <dir> setting at the end of argument list
+FOUND_TEST_DIR=0
+
+testsarray=( "$@" )
+
+# a number of tests where we have no or only few errors == they are pretty stable; we can choose them with command line param default
+DEFAULTTESTS="com/sun/crypto java/beans java/io java/lang java/math java/net java/nio java/rmi java/security java/sql java/text java/time java/util javax/crypto javax/imageio javax/management javax/net javax/script javax/security javax/xml jdk sun/misc sun/net sun/nio sun/rmi sun/reflect sun/security tools vm"
+# adjust the tests on Windows/Cygwin, we still have too much issues with some test groups
+if test x"$ISCYGWIN" = "x1"
+then
+  DEFAULTTESTS="com/sun/crypto java/beans java/io java/lang java/math java/security java/sql java/text java/time java/util javax/crypto javax/imageio javax/net javax/script javax/security javax/xml jdk sun/misc sun/net sun/nio sun/rmi sun/reflect sun/security tools vm"
+fi
+
+# support testing HS / all tests
+DEFAULTTESTS_HS=runtime
+TESTS=""
+
+# derive the test-directory and exclude lists from the file "source_information.txt" which is
+if [ -f source_information.txt ]; then
+  srcdir=`cat source_information.txt`
+  echo "source directory $srcdir (used for location of the jtreg tests) found in local file source_information.txt"
+# TESTDIR=$srcdir/$JTREG_VERSION/jdk/test
+  TESTDIR=$srcdir/test/jdk
+  
+  OWN_EXCLUDE_LIST=$TESTDIR/ProblemList_2nd.txt

+  then
+    TESTDIR=$srcdir/11/test/jdk
+    # check : what to do with own exclude list ?
+  fi

+  echo "warning - source_information.txt file not found, we might not be able to get the tests and exclude list(s)"

+    FOUND_JDK_DIR=0
+    # remove the last two parameters -jdkdir <dir>
+    unset testsarray[${#testsarray[@]}-1]
+    unset testsarray[${#testsarray[@]}-1]
+  else
+    if test x"$FOUND_TEST_DIR" = "x1"
+    then
+      TESTDIR=$argument
+      OWN_EXCLUDE_LIST=$TESTDIR/ProblemList_2nd.txt
+      FOUND_TEST_DIR=0
+      # when setting -testdir we need to have the main /test-folder  parallel to the repo we run the tests from

+      if [ ! -d "$srcdir/test" ]; then
+        echo " "
+        echo "******************************************************************************************************************"
+        echo "***** WARNING : $srcdir/test does not exist, you might need this directory or a softlink to 9/test *****"
+        echo "******************************************************************************************************************"
+        echo " "
+      fi
+      # remove the last two parameters
+      unset testsarray[${#testsarray[@]}-1]
+      unset testsarray[${#testsarray[@]}-1]
+    else
+      if test x"$argument" = "x-jdkdir" -o x"$argument" = "x-testdir"
+      then
+        if test x"$argument" = "x-jdkdir"
+        then

+        else
+          echo "parameter -testdir has been passed to $0"
+          FOUND_TEST_DIR=1
+        fi

+              OWN_EXCLUDE_LIST=""
+            else
+              # "sum up" the tests passed in the arguments
+              TESTS="$TESTS $argument"
+            fi
+          fi
+        fi
+      fi
+    fi
+  fi

+if test x"$default_java_text" = "x"
+then

+JAVAOPTS="-javaoption:-Dhttp.proxyHost=proxy -javaoption:-Dhttp.proxyPort=8080 -javaoption:-Dhttps.proxyHost=proxy -javaoption:-Dhttps.proxyPort=8080 -javaoption:-Dhttp.nonProxyHosts=\"localhost|127.0.0.1|10.*|*.sap.corp|*.wdf.sap.corp\" -javaoption:-Djava.utils.prefs.userRoot=$TMPDIR -Djava.io.tmpdir=$TMPDIR"
+
+# warn in case that JAVA_HOME is set, because this picked up by .../bin/jtreg
+if test x"$JAVA_HOME" != x""
+then
+  echo "*** ATTENTION *** - JAVA_HOME is set (to $JAVA_HOME), this might be picked up by the jtreg run script to choose the tested VM."
+fi
+

+#  java/lang/management/ThreadMXBean/LockedSynchronizers.java

+# however on the Oracle VM, this flag is not known so we must not set it
+# check for SAPJVM specific files that do not exist in the Oracle/OpenJDK VM
+# previously buildinfo.txt was used but this is present as well in the SAP internal OpenJDK
+
+default_vm_options=""
+
+if test -f $VM_VERSION/src_ecc.zip; then
+  echo "$VM_VERSION/src_ecc.zip present, seems it is a SAPJVM"
+  default_vm_options="-vmoption:-XX:+PrintConcurrentLocksDetailed"
+fi
+if test -f $VM_VERSION/jre/lib/src_ecc.zip; then
+  echo "$VM_VERSION/jre/lib/src_ecc.zip present, seems it is a SAPJVM"
+  default_vm_options="-vmoption:-XX:+PrintConcurrentLocksDetailed"
+fi
+# jdk8 only
+if test -f $VM_VERSION/lib/jvmx.jar; then
+  echo "$VM_VERSION/lib/jvmx.jar present, seems it is a SAPJVM"
+  default_vm_options="-vmoption:-XX:+PrintConcurrentLocksDetailed"
+fi
+
+# when running with SAPJVM 11, always set the native library path
+
+if test x"$default_vm_options" != x""
+then
+  if test x"$JTREG_VERSION" = x"11"
+  then
+    outputpath="`cd $0;pwd`"
+    natives="-nativepath:$outputpath/11/images/test/hotspot/jtreg/native"
+    OTHER_JTREG_OPTIONS="$OTHER_JTREG_OPTIONS $natives"
+  fi
+fi
+
+# 
+# some info about the jtreg parameters:
+#  -exclude:list  passes over our exclude list (also know as ProblemList in the jtreg context)
+#  -dir:jtregdir  root directory where the jtreg tests reside
+#  -retain:...    specifies the test groups where files are kept after test execution
+#  -w directoy    working directory of the tests
+#  -r directory   directory where the reports are stored at the end of the test run
+echo "Executing jtreg tests with $JTREG -dir:$TESTDIR -exclude:jtregbase$JTREG_VERSION/collected_problemlist.txt $JTREGFLAGS -jdk:$VM_VERSION -retain:all -w jtregbase$JTREG_VERSION/workdir -r jtregbase$JTREG_VERSION/reportdir $JAVAOPTS $OTHER_JTREG_OPTIONS $default_vm_options $TESTS"
+
+$JTREG -dir:$TESTDIR $CYG_ADDENV -exclude:jtregbase$JTREG_VERSION/collected_problemlist.txt $JTREGFLAGS -jdk:$VM_VERSION -retain:all -w jtregbase$JTREG_VERSION/workdir -r jtregbase$JTREG_VERSION/reportdir $JAVAOPTS $OTHER_JTREG_OPTIONS $default_vm_options $TESTS
+
+# HPUX has differing date command
+if test x"`uname`" = x"HP-UX"
+then
+  endtime=`date -u +%H:%M:%S`
+else
+  endtime=`date +%k:%M:%S`
+fi
+  
+echo "current test run started at $starttime ."
+echo "current test run finished at $endtime ."
